The implementation follows the same conventions as `osKernelLock` and `osKernelUnlock` in the same file:

1. **ISR guard** — returns `osErrorISR` if called from an interrupt context, matching the other functions.
2. **Restore logic** — if `lock > 0`, calls `k_sched_lock()`; otherwise calls `k_sched_unlock()`. This matches the CMSIS RTOS v2 spec where the lock state values returned by `osKernelLock`/`osKernelUnlock` are 0 (unlocked) or non-zero (locked).
3. **Return value** — returns `_current->base.sched_locked` (the new lock state after restoration), which is 0 if now unlocked or non-zero if locked. This matches the spec: "Returns: 0 if kernel was not locked after restoration, non-zero if kernel was locked after restoration."


============================================================
=== Diff ===
============================================================
--- subsys/portability/cmsis_rtos_v2/kernel.c
+++ subsys/portability/cmsis_rtos_v2/kernel.c
@@ -70,7 +70,17 @@
  */
 int32_t osKernelRestoreLock(int32_t lock)
 {
-    /* MASKED - implement this function */
+	if (k_is_in_isr()) {
+		return osErrorISR;
+	}
+
+	if (lock > 0) {
+		k_sched_lock();
+	} else {
+		k_sched_unlock();
+	}
+
+	return _current->base.sched_locked;
 }
 
